    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Common and relatively large, smooth-bodied isopod that readily rolls into a ball when disturbed. Abdominal segments fused. Colouration variable, but usually mottled in browns and yellows. Most characteristic features are the unusually flatted body, rows of short longitudinal ridges on each thoracic segment; broadly triangular and bluntlyâ€“pointed pleotelson and truncated tips to the inner branches of the uropods.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_406",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 15 mm, excluding antennae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_407",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to region.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to about Port Alfred.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_408",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common under boulders on rocky shores and shallow reefs.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_409",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Not specifically known, but thought to feed on algae and possibly other organic debris.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_410",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>As with all isopods the eggs are retained within a marsupial pouch between the walking legs of females and hatch into fully-developed juveniles.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_411",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>There are 14 regional species in this common genus, all of which have an entire pleotelson (not distally rolled or notched). The various species are distinguished mainly by ornamentation and shape of the pleotelson and shape of the uropods. This species is particularly flat and has very broad uropods, but could easily be confused with several others, such as <i>E. varicolor</i> (which has two small dorsal ridges near base of pleotelson and rounded tips to uropods) and <i>E. laeviusculum</i> (semi-circle of small tubercles on pleotelson).</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_412",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 92).<br><br>Kensley, B (1978). Guide to the Marine Isopods of Southern Africa. <i>Trustees of the South African Museum</i>, Cape Town. 173 pp. (p. 106).",
